<TITLE> Egypt can manage subsidy costs:finance minister </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 CAIRO, April 21 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Egyptian Finance Minister Youssef Boutros-Ghali said on Monday that the cost of food and energy subsidies would continue to rise in the 2008/9 financial year, but he could keep the budget deficit level stable. The minister told Reuters in an interview that the cost of food subsidies would rise to 20 billion Egyptian pounds ($3.7 billion) from 15 billion this year, which ends on June 30. Energy subsidies would rise to over 60 billion pounds, from 57 billion, he said. But the overall budget deficit would be stable at 6.9 percent of gross domestic product (GDP), he added. "This is an achievement in the sense that despite the massive increase in prices that we have experienced this year in wheat and other products and energy products, we will still achieve the budget deficit target for this year," he said. The minister said that international food prices would stabilise and that he wanted to raise public-sector salaries by more than 15 percent in July if he could do so without adding to the budget defic
